24 Mar 2017 21:07






This is hideous, but that's obviously the point.

The opening recovery notes have a plausible voice and development to them; I particularly like the regional stuff, the sting at the club, and the failure to recover the -1 instance at Oriol's place. I love  it's the sort of stylistic wrong-footing which I always relish pulling off in my own articles.

What really impresses me about the article is how thematically consistent it manages to be while also indulging in out-there concept-salad weirdness. The slowly degenerating nature of the pick-up manual's advice actually makes a reasonable amount of thematic sense as a horrific Juvenalian satire of pick-up-artist misogyny, one which goes above and beyond the Stepford Wives realisation that the end-point of sexually-motivated misogyny is the murderous replacement of real women with pliant, submissive automata.

When people fall for an ideological, misogynist take on human social behaviour which emphasises, over and over, that women are objects that can be programmed if you just understand the 'secret code' for seducing them, a code held by the select enlightened few men, is it any surprise that this advice grows ever more bizarre and demented? Once you've claimed that all human sexual behaviour can be reduced to a set of rigid principles, is it surprising that this reduction is totally arbitrary, esoteric, and unhinged? Is the monstrous surgeon created from the book's advice a literalisation of the PUA initiate's need to follow someone else's misogynistic schema, because of their inadequacies and low self-esteem? Once a man decides they're willing to completely refashion their personality and morality to fit another's ideology, in order to get laid, can it come as a surprise that this man would be willingly to break and distort their body for the same purpose?

This isn't the sort of piece I can say 'enjoyed', strictly speaking. but it is a piece I respect and which I found fascinating.





